{"mem_mp79e15o_45755211431e":{"concepts":[],"content":"ML DEPLOY PROJECT STATUS - 2026-05-16\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n‚úÖ Documentation Restructuring: COMPLETED (Phases 1-4 finished)\n‚úÖ Architecture Framework: Ratified with contracts, domains, topologies  \n‚úÖ Implementation Scaffolding: Local vertical slice with Web UI contracts\n‚úÖ Tooling Stack: Nix, Docker (Floci/K3s/Slurm), Terranix/OpenTofu\n‚úÖ Governance Framework: Spec-first implementation gating\n\nNEXT STE PRIORITIES:\n1. Contract Automation & Runtime Integration\n   - Connect governance gates into orchestration paths\n   - Implement automated validation for Web UI contracts\n   - Add real-time compliance checks for MLflow operations\n\n2. Multi-Topology Implementation  \n   - Local vertical slice ‚Üí distributed training ‚Üí batch inference ‚Üí online serving\n   - Lambda.ai Slurm integration for distributed workloads\n   - AWS batch inference with lineage controls\n   - Online inference with rollout/rollback capabilities\n\n3. Web UI Execution Flow\n   - Immutable notebook semantics with source validation\n   - Version-controlled execution requests\n   - Connect runtime adapters to actual schedulers\n\n4. Observability & Monitoring\n   - Enhanced metrics collection with cost attribution\n   - Drift detection for model performance\n   - Alerting system with thresholds and notifications\n\nKEY DECISIONS NEEDED:\n- Scope prioritization: distributed training vs batch inference next\n- Resource allocation: cloud infrastructure vs local development focus  \n- Team structure: ML engineering vs DevOps responsibilities\n\nTECHNICAL DEBT AREAS:\n- Missing scheduler client integrations (Slurm/Kubernetes)\n- Incomplete observability features beyond MLflow+Floci\n- Need for automated artifact freshness validation in CI/CD\n\nBEST PRACTICES ESTABLISHED:\n- Documentation self-sufficiency requirements\n- Spec-first development patterns with governance gating\n- Contract-first implementation approach\n- Wiki as living memory layer for continuous knowledge capture","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:36:42.971Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79e15o_45755211431e","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"ML DEPLOY PROJECT STATUS - 2026-05-16\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n‚úÖ Documentation Restructur","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:36:42.971Z","version":1},"mem_mp79q796_1585661822e4":{"concepts":[],"content":"WIKI OVERVIEW - Living Knowledge Layer for ML Deploy Project\n\nPURPOSE: The wiki serves as the repository's long-term memory layer, providing curated synthesized knowledge that lets future agents avoid re-reading the entire repository every session.\n\nSTRUCTURE:\n- docs/wiki/index.md - Primary router and catalog\n- docs/wiki/overview.md - High-level project summary  \n- docs/wiki/current-state.md - Honest repo snapshot and gaps\n- docs/wiki/log.md - Append-only change log\n- docs/wiki/architecture/ - Technical structure\n- docs/wiki/runbooks/ - Commands and operational steps\n- docs/wiki/decisions/ - Durable decisions and rationale\n- docs/wiki/sources/ - Synthesized pages for important raw source files\n- docs/wiki/plans/ - Active project plans and tracking\n- docs/wiki/revisions/ - Artifacts for significant wiki-affecting updates\n- docs/wiki/queries/ - Reusable answers\n- docs/wiki/archive/ - Superseded or demoted pages\n\nWORKFLOW:\n1. At task start: Read index.md, relevant routed pages, raw files as needed\n2. During task: Discover durable facts, decisions, constraints, open questions ‚Üí fold into wiki\n3. Before final response: Update all relevant wiki pages if substantive changes occurred\n\nPAGE CONVENTIONS:\n- Compact, high-signal pages\n- Include what it's for, when to read, links to sources, concise facts\n- Explicit uncertainty where needed\n- Progress tracking for active plans\n- Completion status and next steps\n- Risk assessment and dependencies\n\nQUALITY BAR: Wiki should help future agents quickly answer:\n- What is this repo?\n- What exists right now?\n- How do I run it?\n- What are important constraints?\n- What changed recently?\n- Which raw files matter for this task?","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:46:10.746Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79q796_1585661822e4","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"WIKI OVERVIEW - Living Knowledge Layer for ML Deploy Project\n\nPURPOSE: The wiki ","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:46:10.746Z","version":1},"mem_mp79qoa2_82e1a8035c56":{"concepts":[],"content":"TARGET SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE - Core Design Decisions\n\nMISSION: Build extensive reference documentation with code examples for full ML lifecycle from development to distributed production deployment.\n\nSCOPE BOUNDARY:\n- Model development, experiment tracking, reproducible training\n- Packaging and local inference orchestration  \n- Infrastructure provisioning, distributed compute workflows\n- Deployment patterns, monitoring and cost visibility\n- Security and lineage requirements across the stack\n\nTECHNOLOGY DIRECTION:\n- Language: Python only (where practical)\n- OS: Linux only\n- Reproducible development: Docker required, Nix as helper\n- ML stack: nbdev 3 (Quarto), PyTorch, GPU support, MLflow\n- Storage: PostgreSQL backend + S3 artifact store for MLflow\n- Documentation: Quarto via nbdev 3 with Mermaid diagrams\n- Infrastructure: Terranix + OpenTofu JSON generation\n- Compute: Lambda.ai/Slurm for distributed, AWS Kubernetes for platform services\n\nCROSS-CUTTING REQUIREMENTS:\n- Security: OIDC-backed identity + centralized authorization\n- Data lineage, experiment traceability, model traceability  \n- Reproducibility, auditable assistant interactions\n- Parallel DEV‚ÜíUAT‚ÜíREGRESSION‚ÜíPROD promotion gates\n\nPRIMARY AUDIENCE: ML engineers in hedge funds\nCONTENT DEPTH: Architecture + runnable end-to-end patterns, not just prototypes\n\nDEFAULT STACKS:\n- Monitoring: Evidently + Prometheus + Grafana + MLflow\n- Cost monitoring: AWS Cost Explorer/CUR/Athena + Python attribution layer\n- Assistant integration: MLflow, observability, cost visibility, infrastructure interrogation\n\nDOCUMENTATION DELIVERY: nbdev 3 with Quarto - notebooks in nbs/ are source of truth\n\nCOVERAGE PRIORITIES:\n- Distributed training on Lambda.ai/Slurm\n- Batch inference on AWS infrastructure  \n- Online inference with rollout/rollback capabilities\n\nLINEAGE SCOPE: Datasets ‚Üí Features/Transformations ‚Üí Experiments ‚Üí Model Artifacts ‚Üí Model Versions ‚Üí Deployments ‚Üí Operational Runs","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:46:32.809Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79qoa2_82e1a8035c56","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"TARGET SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE - Core Design Decisions\n\nMISSION: Build extensive ref","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:46:32.809Z","version":1},"mem_mp79rinw_080426341148":{"concepts":[],"content":"PROJECT SCOPE AND CONSTRAINTS - Core Working Rules\n\nCURRENT PURPOSE: Extensive reference documentation with code examples covering ML lifecycle from development to distributed production.\n\nHARD CONSTRAINTS:\n1. Python only (where practical), Linux only, PyTorch only with GPU support\n2. Docker required for reproducible development (Nix as helper only)\n3. MLflow mandatory with PostgreSQL backend + S3 artifact store\n4. Local architecture replicates production storage/control planes (PostgreSQL + S3-compatible like Floci)\n5. Lambda.ai for distributed compute with Slurm orchestration/redundancy\n6. AWS for platform services with Kubernetes substrate\n7. Notebook Web UI required for ML engineers to trigger runs without code edits\n8. Infrastructure: Nix-driven Terranix ‚Üí OpenTofu JSON generation (minimal hand-written Terraform)\n9. Security, data lineage, experiment/model traceability, reproducibility are permanent requirements\n\nAUDIENCE AND SCOPE:\n- Primary audience: ML engineers in hedge funds\n- Material depth: Architecture + runnable end-to-end patterns\n- Coverage: All three topologies - distributed training, batch inference, online inference\n- AWS coverage: Full production patterns (not just prototypes)\n- Lineage scope: Datasets ‚Üí Features ‚Üí Experiments ‚Üí Model Artifacts ‚Üí Model Versions ‚Üí Deployments ‚Üí Operational Runs\n\nDEFAULT STACKS:\n- Monitoring: Evidently + Prometheus + Grafana + MLflow\n- Cost monitoring: AWS Cost Explorer/CUR/Athena/Budgets + Python attribution for Lambda.ai\n- MCP scope: MLflow, observability, cost visibility, infrastructure interrogation\n\nWORKING MODE: Specification-first - architecture and documentation quality priority, implementation gated behind spec-quality readiness or explicit user authorization\n\nIMPLEMENTATION QUESTIONS:\n- Python-driven, Linux/PyTorch/GPU support?\n- Preserves security/data lineage/reproducibility?\n- Fits MLflow + PostgreSQL/S3 + Terranix/OpenTofu + Lambda.ai(Slurm) + AWS(Kubernetes) direction?\n\nOPEN ITEMS REQUIRING AGREEMENT:\n- Explicit spec-quality gate definition (pass criteria, approvers, required sections)\n- Notebook-promotion approval workflow from local to cloud execution\n- Normalized run-state contract across local/Slurm/Kubernetes backends\n- Nix vs Docker boundary in practice\n- Separation of reusable platform vs hedge-fund-specific guidance","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:47:12.187Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79rinw_080426341148","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"PROJECT SCOPE AND CONSTRAINTS - Core Working Rules\n\nCURRENT PURPOSE: Extensive r","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:47:12.187Z","version":1},"mem_mp79s8oo_9ae112576749":{"concepts":[],"content":"FIRST VERTICAL SLICE - Local Implementation Reference\n\nPURPOSE: Smallest end-to-end architecture proof focusing on local development without premature scope broadening.\n\nSLICE BOUNDARY: Composes EX-01 (local training + MLflow), EX-02 (artifact packaging + version registration), EX-03 (local inference + prediction logging)\n\nSCOPE: Local development topology only - no distributed training or AWS rollout\n\nINPUTS:\n- Versioned local dataset identifier\n- Transformation spec/version id  \n- Training config/hyperparameters\n- Local runtime/container identity\n- Model serving request schema version\n\nOUTPUTS:\n- MLflow run with required traceability metadata\n- Packaged model artifact with schema/compatibility metadata\n- Model version record referencing artifact\n- Local serving deployment record\n- Prediction logs linked to model/deployment identifiers\n\nCONTRACT OBLIGATIONS:\n- Data lineage baseline\n- Experiment traceability baseline  \n- Model artifact baseline\n- Deployment baseline (local form)\n- Prediction logging baseline\n\nSUCCESS CRITERIA:\n1. Full prediction traceability: prediction ‚Üí model version ‚Üí training run ‚Üí dataset/transformation versions\n2. Artifact metadata sufficient for serving compatibility without code spelunking\n3. Local inference from packaged artifact metadata (not hidden notebook state)\n4. Request-level diagnosis context in local testing logs\n5. Repeatable workflow with changed hyperparameters + full traceability\n\nCURRENT IMPLEMENTATION:\n- ‚úÖ ml_deploy/vertical_slice.py (orchestration + metadata emission + local prediction)\n- ‚úÖ tests/test_vertical_slice.py (end-to-end local slice checks)\n- ‚úÖ File-backed MLflow tracking for local execution\n- ‚úÖ Artifact bundle and model-version JSON records\n- ‚úÖ Local deployment record generation\n- ‚úÖ Prediction JSONL logging with model/deployment linkage\n\nNOT YET IMPLEMENTED:\n- Docker-first execution path\n- Remote/distributed or AWS-integrated flows\n\nEXPLICIT NON-GOALS:\n- Distributed compute on Lambda.ai\n- Production-grade rollout/canary policy\n- Full cross-provider cost analytics\n- Docs-delivery companion service\n\nHANDOFF NOTES:\n- EX-04: Extends to distributed training while preserving traceability\n- EX-05/EX-06: Reuses artifact/deployment interfaces in batch/online topologies","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:47:45.911Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79s8oo_9ae112576749","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"FIRST VERTICAL SLICE - Local Implementation Reference\n\nPURPOSE: Smallest end-to-","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:47:45.911Z","version":1},"mem_mp79tyef_58aa556ab5bc":{"concepts":[],"content":"CROSS-CUTTING CONTRACTS - System-Wide Invariants\n\nPURPOSE: Define reusable invariants that every domain and topology must obey to prevent inconsistent security, ad hoc lineage, incomplete traceability, incompatible packaging, deployment ambiguity, unusable logs, and weak cost attribution.\n\nCONTRACTS & OWNERSHIP:\n1. Security Baseline (governance domain) - identity, secrets, network, access, audit minimums\n   - Validation: design review, deployment approval, incident review\n2. Data Lineage Baseline (data domain) - dataset/transformation provenance fields\n   - Validation: dataset publish, transformation publish, training-job submission  \n3. Experiment Traceability Baseline (training domain) - experiment/training metadata\n   - Validation: training start/end, MLflow run checks, promotion gate\n4. Model Artifact Baseline (artifact domain) - metadata/compatibility requirements\n   - Validation: artifact packaging, model registration, serving compatibility checks\n5. Deployment Baseline (serving + governance domains) - deployment record requirements\n   - Validation: rollout approval, deployment record creation, rollback readiness\n6. Prediction Logging Baseline (serving + observability domains) - inference logging requirements\n   - Validation: pre-release checklist, runtime log schema checks, incident triage\n7. Cost Attribution Baseline (cost + infrastructure domains) - spend tagging/attribution\n   - Validation: infra provisioning, cost reports, budget alerting reviews\n\nUSAGE RULES:\n- Domain pages consume these contracts, don't redefine them\n- Topology pages state how they implement these contracts\n- Code examples state which contracts they satisfy and where they intentionally simplify\n- New cross-cutting rules must either extend existing contracts or create new explicit contracts\n\nENFORCEMENT: Each contract is treated as an interface with explicit ownership and validation points at key system gates","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:49:05.894Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79tyef_58aa556ab5bc","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"CROSS-CUTTING CONTRACTS - System-Wide Invariants\n\nPURPOSE: Define reusable invar","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:49:05.894Z","version":1},"mem_mp79urhd_4dd808eca4b5":{"concepts":[],"content":"BOUNDED DOMAINS - Architecture Responsibility Areas\n\nPURPOSE: Turn architecture skeleton's bounded domains into explicit planning surfaces, resolving ambiguous responsibilities and clarifying ownership.\n\nDOMAINS & RESPONSIBILITIES:\n\n1. Data Domain - datasets, schemas, provenance, transformation lineage\n   - Owns: Dataset management, feature engineering pipelines, data validation, lineage tracking\n   - Contracts: Data Lineage Baseline\n   - Relevant to: All topologies requiring input data\n\n2. Training Domain - PyTorch training, GPU execution, distributed behavior, experiment traceability  \n   - Owns: Model training workflows, hyperparameter optimization, distributed coordination, experiment tracking\n   - Contracts: Experiment Traceability Baseline\n   - Relevant to: Local development, distributed training topologies\n\n3. Artifact Domain - model packaging, registry, versioning, promotion\n   - Owns: Model artifact creation, version management, compatibility schemas, promotion workflows\n   - Contracts: Model Artifact Baseline\n   - Relevant to: All topologies producing model artifacts\n\n4. Serving Domain - local serving, batch/online inference, rollout behavior\n   - Owns: Inference service deployment, batch processing, online serving, canary/rollback logic\n   - Contracts: Deployment Baseline, Prediction Logging Baseline\n   - Relevant to: Batch inference, online inference topologies\n\n5. Infrastructure Domain - AWS, Lambda.ai, networking, storage, Terranix/OpenTofu\n   - Owns: Cloud resource provisioning, network configuration, storage systems, IaC generation\n   - Contracts: Cost Attribution Baseline (infrastructure aspects)\n   - Relevant to: All topologies requiring infrastructure\n\n6. Observability Domain - metrics, logs, traces, drift, quality, alerting\n   - Owns: Monitoring systems, logging pipelines, drift detection, quality metrics, alerting\n   - Contracts: Prediction Logging Baseline (observability aspects)\n   - Relevant to: All topologies requiring monitoring\n\n7. Governance Domain - security, approvals, auditability, IAM, policy boundaries\n   - Owns: Security controls, approval workflows, audit logging, policy enforcement, compliance\n   - Contracts: Security Baseline\n   - Relevant to: All topologies requiring security/authorization\n\n8. Cost Domain - spend attribution, reporting, budgets, unit economics\n   - Owns: Cost tracking, budget management, spend attribution, cost optimization\n   - Contracts: Cost Attribution Baseline\n   - Relevant to: All topologies with infrastructure costs\n\nUSAGE RULES:\n- Each domain page should clarify what it owns vs doesn't own\n- Define which lifecycle stages each domain covers\n- Specify which contracts each domain consumes\n- Identify which topologies each domain is most relevant to\n- Document open questions within each domain\n- Resolve ambiguous responsibilities here before creating examples/implementation","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:49:43.583Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79urhd_4dd808eca4b5","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"BOUNDED DOMAINS - Architecture Responsibility Areas\n\nPURPOSE: Turn architecture ","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:49:43.583Z","version":1},"mem_mp79vasp_1ce65f8ee26a":{"concepts":[],"content":"REFERENCE TOPOLOGIES - Concrete Deployment Shapes\n\nPURPOSE: Map architecture into concrete deployment shapes answering which domains are active, which contracts matter, operational boundaries, and local vs production distinctions.\n\nTOPOLOGIES & CHARACTERISTICS:\n\n1. Local Development and Single-Node Training\n   - Domains active: Data, Training, Artifact, Serving (local), Infrastructure (local)\n   - Key contracts: Data Lineage, Experiment Traceability, Model Artifact, Deployment (local), Prediction Logging\n   - Scope: Docker-based local iteration, local serving, single-node GPU training\n   - Operational boundaries: Local-only, production-like architecture but local execution\n   - Flow specs: Local data ‚Üí training ‚Üí artifact packaging ‚Üí local serving ‚Üí prediction logging\n\n2. Distributed Training on Lambda.ai\n   - Domains active: Data, Training, Artifact, Infrastructure (Lambda.ai), Governance\n   - Key contracts: Data Lineage, Experiment Traceability, Model Artifact, Cost Attribution\n   - Scope: Multi-GPU or multi-node remote training on Lambda.ai with Slurm coordination\n   - Operational boundaries: Remote compute with local control plane\n   - Flow specs: Dataset upload ‚Üí distributed training ‚Üí artifact packaging ‚Üí cost tracking ‚Üí model promotion\n\n3. Batch Inference on AWS Integrated Infrastructure\n   - Domains active: Data, Serving, Infrastructure (AWS), Observability, Cost\n   - Key contracts: Deployment Baseline, Prediction Logging Baseline, Cost Attribution Baseline\n   - Scope: Scheduled/event-driven offline inference with lineage and cost controls\n   - Operational boundaries: Production-grade with cost attribution and lineage tracking\n   - Flow specs: Batch requests ‚Üí model deployment ‚Üí batch processing ‚Üí prediction logging ‚Üí cost attribution\n\n4. Online Inference under Production Controls\n   - Domains active: Serving, Infrastructure (AWS), Observability, Governance, Cost\n   - Key contracts: Deployment Baseline, Prediction Logging Baseline, Security Baseline, Cost Attribution\n   - Scope: Kubernetes-based request/response serving with deployment/observability controls\n   - Operational boundaries: Production-grade with security, monitoring, and rollout controls\n   - Flow specs: Request ‚Üí deployment rollout ‚Üí online serving ‚Üí prediction logging ‚Üí monitoring ‚Üí drift detection\n\nIMPLEMENTATION RULES:\n- Topology pages implement architecture and contracts, don't redefine domain ownership\n- Each topology includes explicit control/data/artifact flows and contract checkpoints\n- Focus on concrete deployment shapes rather than abstract architecture\n- Maintain consistency across topologies while adapting to specific runtime constraints","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:50:08.616Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79vasp_1ce65f8ee26a","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"REFERENCE TOPOLOGIES - Concrete Deployment Shapes\n\nPURPOSE: Map architecture int","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:50:08.616Z","version":1},"mem_mp79we26_975e29f3a28c":{"concepts":[],"content":"REFERENCE ARCHITECTURE SKELETON - Canonical Design Framework\n\nMISSION: Python-first reference for ML engineers covering full PyTorch lifecycle from development to distributed production.\n\nARCHITECTURAL PRINCIPLES:\n1. Lifecycle first - organize around real ML system lifecycle, not tools alone\n2. Bounded domains - assign each concern clear boundaries  \n3. Cross-cutting contracts - define lineage/security/traceability once, apply everywhere\n4. Topology separation - keep local dev, distributed training, batch, online inference distinct\n5. Python-first implementation - prefer Python unless platform forces otherwise\n6. Production realism - runnable patterns, not toy snippets\n7. Security by default - design input, not hardening pass\n8. Lineage by construction - every major artifact attributable and reconstructable\n9. Assistant augmentation - explicit auditable interfaces over canonical systems\n\nLIFECYCLE SPINE (canonical end-to-end):\n1. Data intake and dataset versioning\n2. Feature/transformation definition  \n3. Experiment specification\n4. Training execution\n5. Evaluation and validation\n6. Model packaging\n7. Model registration and promotion\n8. Local serving\n9. Distributed training\n10. Batch inference\n11. Online inference\n12. Monitoring and alerting\n13. Cost governance\n14. Incident response and rollback\n\nCORE SYSTEM OBJECTS:\n- Dataset version (immutable data snapshot with provenance)\n- Transformation spec (feature logic + preprocessing definition)\n- Experiment run (tracked execution with lineage/artifacts)\n- Training job (compute execution, local/distributed)\n- Model artifact (serialized model + metadata)\n- Model version (promoted registry entry with validation)\n- Deployment record (where model version was deployed)\n- Inference run (batch/online prediction events)\n- Cost record (spend attribution by environment/workload/model/run/deployment)\n- Assistant interaction record (auditable assistant automation context)\n\nARCHITECTURAL DOMAINS:\n1. Data - data intake, dataset versioning, schemas, provenance, data quality\n2. Training - PyTorch code, training config, GPU execution, distributed behavior, evaluation\n3. Artifact - model packaging, registry, versioning, promotion, compatibility constraints\n4. Serving - local inference, online/batch contracts, model loading, inference runtime\n5. Infrastructure - Terranix/OpenTofu, AWS resources, Lambda.ai, networking, storage\n6. Observability - metrics, logs, traces, drift monitoring, alerting\n7. Governance - security, IAM, secret handling, auditability, approval boundaries\n8. Cost - spend attribution, tagging, reporting, budgets, unit economics\n\nCROSS-CUTTING CONTRACTS (7 system-wide invariants):\nA. Security baseline - identity, secrets, network, access, audit trails\nB. Data lineage baseline - source origin, version, schema, code reference, consumers  \nC. Experiment traceability - code revision, environment, dataset/transformation versions, hyperparameters, artifacts\nD. Model artifact baseline - training origin, framework/serialization, schema, evaluation, serving modes\nE. Deployment baseline - model version, target environment, infra revision, rollback target, monitoring\nF. Prediction logging baseline - model version used, request ID, input schema, output capture, latency, traceability\nG. Cost attribution baseline - environment, workload type, owning system, experiment/job/deployment linkage\n\nREFERENCE TOPOLOGIES (4 concrete deployment shapes):\nA. Local Development - Docker iteration, local serving, single-node GPU training\nB. Distributed Training - Lambda.ai multi-GPU/multi-node with Slurm coordination\nC. Batch Inference - AWS scheduled/event-driven with lineage and cost controls  \nD. Online Inference - Kubernetes request/response with deployment/observability controls\n\nASSISTANT AUGMENTATION SURFACES:\n- Experiment/run inspection\n- Model/version inspection  \n- Deployment-state inspection\n- Alert/metric review\n- Cost review\n- Documentation retrieval\n\nDOCUMENTATION DELIVERY:\n- Markdown-in-git canonical\n- Dynamic services separate from model-serving\n- Structured metadata/search/navigation optional\n- Authenticated write/edit helpers remain auditable\n\nSEPARATION-OF-CONCERNS RULES:\n- Training pages don't hide infrastructure decisions\n- Serving pages don't redefine model packaging contracts\n- Monitoring pages don't redefine logging requirements ad hoc  \n- Security policy not restated differently per topology\n- Cost reporting not bolted on later\n- Assistant integrations don't become second control plane\n- Documentation delivery separate from model-serving delivery\n- Examples point back to domains and contracts\n\nDEFAULT STACK:\n- Training: PyTorch + GPU\n- Tracking: MLflow\n- Storage: PostgreSQL + S3 for MLflow\n- Local serving: nbdev-exported Python interfaces\n- Infrastructure: Terranix/OpenTofu from flake+devenv\n- Distributed: Lambda.ai + Slurm coordination\n- Platform: AWS Kubernetes for non-Lambda.ai services\n- Reproducible: Docker (Nix optional helper)\n- Monitoring: Evidently + Prometheus/Grafana + MLflow\n- Cost: AWS CUR/Athena/Budgets + Python attribution\n- Assistant: MLflow + observability + cost + infrastructure interrogation via MCP","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:50:59.500Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79we26_975e29f3a28c","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"REFERENCE ARCHITECTURE SKELETON - Canonical Design Framework\n\nMISSION: Python-fi","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:50:59.500Z","version":1},"mem_mp79wy8o_545d129e7632":{"concepts":[],"content":"LOCAL VERTICAL SLICE IMPLEMENTATION - First Architecture Slice in Code\n\nROLE: Concrete local implementation for first architecture slice (EX-01, EX-02, EX-03)\n\nOWNERSHIP: Generated by nbdev from nbs/06_vertical_slice.qmd - do not hand-edit\n\nMAIN FUNCTIONS:\n- generate_synthetic_dataset() - deterministic synthetic training data generation\n- prepare_training_data() - split + scale pipeline  \n- train_with_traceability() - MLflow-tracked training with lineage/traceability params\n- package_and_register_model() - writes model/scaler bundle + artifact/model-version metadata\n- promote_model_artifact() - enforces DEV->UAT->REGRESSION->PROD gate checks\n- create_local_deployment_record() - writes deployment record JSON for local serving\n- predict_and_log() - local prediction helper with JSONL prediction logs + deployment/model linkage\n- execute_first_vertical_slice() - orchestration helper running whole local flow\n\nRECORDS EMITTED:\n- artifact_metadata.json (model artifact metadata)\n- model_version.json (model version with stage/gate booleans)\n- deployment_record.json (local deployment metadata)\n- prediction_logs.jsonl (prediction logs with request/model/deployment linkage)\n\nCONTRACT RELEVANT BEHAVIOR:\n- Training records capture dataset/transformation/code/container/compute metadata\n- Artifact records capture run origin, schemas, serving modes, evaluation summary  \n- Model-version records include stage/gate booleans for promotion-pipeline checks\n- Deployment records capture model version, rollout metadata, monitoring config reference\n- Prediction logs capture request ID, model version, deployment ID, schema reference, runtime metadata\n\nSCOPE LIMITATIONS:\n- Local development topology only (no distributed training or AWS rollout)\n- File-backed MLflow tracking (not PostgreSQL/S3 yet)\n- Local execution path (no Docker-first execution yet)\n- No remote/distributed or AWS-integrated flows\n\nSUCCESS CRITERIA IMPLEMENTED:\n1. Full prediction traceability (prediction ‚Üí model ‚Üí training ‚Üí dataset/transformation)\n2. Artifact metadata for serving compatibility without code spelunking\n3. Local inference from packaged artifact metadata (not hidden notebook state)\n4. Request-level diagnosis context in local testing logs\n5. Repeatable workflow with changed hyperparameters + full traceability","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:51:25.655Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79wy8o_545d129e7632","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"LOCAL VERTICAL SLICE IMPLEMENTATION - First Architecture Slice in Code\n\nROLE: Co","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:51:25.655Z","version":1},"mem_mp79xh0t_cb5c8eaa8fe8":{"concepts":[],"content":"DISTILLED ALLIUM SPEC - Formal Repository Behavior Baseline\n\nPURPOSE: Compact, formal baseline for current repository behavior during specification-first phase.\n\nCURRENT MODELED BEHAVIOR:\n\n1. Repository Posture & Constraints:\n   - Python/Linux/PyTorch/GPU/MLflow/Terranix+OpenTofu-from-flake+devenv/Lambda.ai/AWS direction\n   - Accepted default monitoring/cost/MCP sets\n   - Infrastructure interrogation when MCP servers available\n\n2. Implemented Shell Behavior:\n   - Shell entry from flake.nix\n   - uv bootstrap when pyproject.toml exists\n   - Jupyter helper expectations\n\n3. Wiki Maintenance Obligations:\n   - AGENTS.md process requirements\n   - Current wiki workflow and quality standards\n\n4. Implementation Gating:\n   - Specification-first block unless explicit confirmation present\n   - Spec quality readiness gating for default implementation allowance\n   - Implementation requires either explicit user confirmation OR both implementation-enabled phase AND passed spec-quality gate\n\n5. Infrastructure MCP Interrogation Gating:\n   - When infra MCP servers available, minimum interrogation coverage required\n   - Explicit scope enforcement\n\n6. Documentation Self-Sufficiency Gating:\n   - Published QMD docs must be sufficient without repository source browsing\n   - Implementation-relevant behavior/config must be visible from published pages\n\n7. Formal Safety Contracts & Invariants:\n   - Promotion gates for model artifacts and MLOps system definitions\n   - MLflow cloud safety posture requirements\n   - Parallel DEV‚ÜíUAT‚ÜíREGRESSION‚ÜíPROD approval gates\n   - Centralized OIDC-backed authorization authority\n   - Capability catalogs and request validation\n\nQUALITY-TIGHTENING CHANGES:\n- fastapi_in_scope defaults to false (aligns with nbdev-first direction)\n- spec_quality_gate_passed modeled as repository state for default implementation allowance\n- AllowImplementationAfterGate requires explicit user confirmation OR (implementation-enabled phase AND passed spec-quality gate)\n\nSCOPE BOUNDARIES:\n- Included: Behavior in repository files, durable constraints from accepted decisions\n- Excluded: External platform internals (AWS, Lambda.ai, MLflow, Prometheus, Grafana), ML implementation not yet added\n\nUSAGE:\n- Baseline for refining behavior with tend\n- Reference point for future spec-code drift checks with weed\n- Update both .allium file and source summary when behavior/constraints change","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:51:49.996Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79xh0t_cb5c8eaa8fe8","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"DISTILLED ALLIUM SPEC - Formal Repository Behavior Baseline\n\nPURPOSE: Compact, f","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:51:49.996Z","version":1},"mem_mp79y060_dbc102a252b7":{"concepts":[],"content":"WEB UI BACKEND CONTRACTS - Immutable Notebook Execution Interface\n\nROLE: Defines thin Python contracts for Web UI backend handling immutable notebook execution and MLflow-linked run visibility\n\nOWNERSHIP: Generated by nbdev from nbs/05_webui_contracts.qmd - do not hand-edit\n\nMAIN FUNCTIONS AND MODELS:\n- build_mlflow_run_url() - stable MLflow run deep-link constructor\n- NotebookRevision - immutable source reference (commit, tag, approved-ref)\n- NotebookExecutionRequest - validated execution request + normalized as_job_spec() output\n- RunVisibility - Web UI run summary view model  \n- summarize_run_for_webui() - metadata-to-summary mapper with status normalization\n\nCONTRACT-RELEVANT BEHAVIOR:\n- Commit references validated as git-style SHA strings\n- Job-spec generation refuses requests without request identity/timestamp defaults\n- Run summaries always include MLflow deep link for operator pivoting\n- Immutable notebook semantics enforced through source reference validation\n- Execution requests trigger runs without modifying notebook source code\n- MLflow integration provides comprehensive run visibility and tracking\n\nSCOPE:\n- Web UI backend request/response contracts\n- Immutable notebook execution semantics\n- MLflow-linked run visibility and summary models\n- Execution adapter normalization interface\n\nNOT YET IMPLEMENTED:\n- Actual backend execution service\n- Environment-specific adapter integrations\n- Remote scheduler client connections","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:52:14.807Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79y060_dbc102a252b7","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"WEB UI BACKEND CONTRACTS - Immutable Notebook Execution Interface\n\nROLE: Defines","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:52:14.807Z","version":1},"mem_mp79yrjy_c8bf33543d9d":{"concepts":[],"content":"EXECUTION BACKENDS - Adapter Layer for Notebook Execution\n\nROLE: Implements execution adapter behavior for notebook runs across local, Slurm, and Kubernetes targets\n\nOWNERSHIP: Generated by nbdev from nbs/08_execution_backends.qmd - do not hand-edit\n\nMAIN COMPONENTS:\n- LocalExecutionAdapter.submit() - normalizes request, executes local runner, emits MLflow-linked run summary\n- ExecutionOrchestrator.submit() - routes normalized requests to local execution or distributed submission payloads\n- map_to_slurm_job_spec() - maps normalized job spec to Slurm submission fields  \n- map_to_kubernetes_job_spec() - maps normalized job spec to Kubernetes Job manifest\n\nPRACTICAL IMPLICATION:\n- Concrete routing layer between Web UI contract requests and backend-specific execution/submission behavior\n- Normalized interface for different execution backends (local, Slurm, Kubernetes)\n- Local execution adapter implements first vertical slice with return RunVisibility\n- Distributed adapters generate platform-specific submission payloads\n\nEXECUTION BACKEND COVERAGE:\n- ‚úÖ Local execution: First vertical slice implementation with MLflow integration\n- ‚úÖ Slurm payload mapping: Maps to Slurm submission fields\n- ‚úÖ Kubernetes payload mapping: Maps to Kubernetes Job manifest\n- ‚ĚĆ Remote scheduler client connections: Not yet implemented\n- ‚ĚĆ Actual backend execution services: Adapters exist but need service connections\n- ‚ĚĆ Status polling and lifecycle management: Only submitted/completed states implemented\n\nCONTRACT INTEGRATION:\n- Receives normalized job specs from Web UI contracts\n- Returns execution status and run visibility summaries\n- Maintains immutable notebook execution semantics\n- Integrates with MLflow for run tracking and visibility","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:52:50.301Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79yrjy_c8bf33543d9d","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"EXECUTION BACKENDS - Adapter Layer for Notebook Execution\n\nROLE: Implements exec","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:52:50.301Z","version":1},"mem_mp79z9bu_cd3c912a0869":{"concepts":[],"content":"GOVERNANCE GATES - Specification-First Implementation Gating\n\nROLE: Provides executable gating decisions for transitions from specification_first to implementation_enabled\n\nMAIN COMPONENTS:\n- RepositoryGovernanceState - tracks repository governance state\n- GovernanceDecision - represents gating decisions with reasoning  \n- request_implementation_transition() - handles implementation transition requests\n\nBEHAVIOR:\n- Blocks transition without explicit confirmation while in specification_first phase\n- Blocks transition when spec_quality_gate_passed is false\n- Returns allowed no-op decision when phase is already implementation_enabled\n- Implements AllowImplementationAfterGate rule from distilled Allium spec\n\nPRACTICAL IMPLICATION:\n- Previously policy-only implementation gate now has code-level state/decision logic\n- Aligns with distilled Allium rule set for implementation gating\n- Provides programmatic interface for repository governance decisions\n- Supports both explicit user confirmation and spec quality gate pathways\n\nINTEGRATION POINTS:\n- Used by runtime orchestration to check implementation permissions\n- Connected to promotion pipeline gate logic\n- Supports no-op requests when repository already implementation_enabled\n- Blocks unauthorized implementation during specification-first phase\n\nSPEC QUALITY GATING:\n- Implementation requires either explicit user confirmation OR\n- Both implementation-enabled phase AND passed spec-quality gate\n- Provides clear decision reasoning for auditability","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:53:13.336Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp79z9bu_cd3c912a0869","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"GOVERNANCE GATES - Specification-First Implementation Gating\n\nROLE: Provides exe","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:53:13.336Z","version":1},"mem_mp7a0mvp_821900fe41c8":{"concepts":[],"content":"JUPYTER AND SHELL OPERATIONS - Development Workflow Commands\n\nSHELL ENTRY:\n- nix develop - Provides flake-defined toolchain, environment variables, optional .env loading\n- Automatic .venv creation/activation with uv sync on entry or explicit request\n- uv sync runs on dependency drift (uv sync --check) or explicit request (UV_SYNC_REQUESTED=1)\n\nDOCKER-FIRST DEVELOPMENT:\n- docker compose -f docker-compose.aws-emulator.yml -f docker-compose.dev.yml up -d --build\n- docker compose -f docker-compose.aws-emulator.yml -f docker-compose.dev.yml exec dev bash\n- Shutdown: docker compose -f docker-compose.dev.yml down\n\nJUPYTER KERNEL MANAGEMENT:\n- nix develop -c start-jupyter --ensure-only - Installs/refreshes ml_ops kernel\n- Uses flake-provided Python runtime with ipykernel (independent of project .venv)\n\nJUPYTER LAB START:\n- nix develop -c start-jupyter - Ensures ml_ops kernel, launches jupyter-lab\n- Disabled token/password auth and XSRF checks for convenience\n\nJUPYTER DATA LOCATIONS:\n- Project Jupyter path: jupyter/\n- Kernel location: jupyter/kernels/ml_ops  \n- Config location: ~/.jupyter\n\nQUARTO DOCUMENTATION:\n- Render without execution: nix develop -c quarto render . --to html --no-execute\n- Helper script: ./scripts/regenerate-html.sh\n- Homepage render: nix develop -c quarto render nbs/index.qmd --to html --no-execute\n- Output: _docs/index.html (forwards to) _docs/nbs/index.html\n\nTESTING AND VALIDATION:\n- Run vertical slice tests: uv sync && uv run python -m unittest discover -s tests -q\n- End-of-task workflow: ./scripts/finalize-task.sh\n  1. Generate Docker artifacts (if nix available)\n  2. nbdev-export --path nbs/\n  3. Quarto render --no-execute\n  4. Unit tests\n- Docker artifact regeneration: python scripts/generate-docker-artifacts.py\n\nKNOWN SHARP EDGES:\n- uv sync required before project dependencies work\n- ipykernel required for Jupyter helpers\n- Quarto render output: _docs/ (not _docs/nbs/)\n- Quarto execution depends on valid kernel path; use --no-execute for validation\n- Jupyter configured for trusted dev environments, not production security","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:54:17.555Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp7a0mvp_821900fe41c8","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"JUPYTER AND SHELL OPERATIONS - Development Workflow Commands\n\nSHELL ENTRY:\n- nix","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:54:17.555Z","version":1},"mem_mp7a28sn_3a585eb07139":{"concepts":[],"content":"WIKI COMPREHENSIVE MEMORY CAPTURE - Complete Project Knowledge Base\n\n## PROJECT OVERVIEW\nThis is a documentation-first, Python-heavy ML deployment reference covering the full lifecycle from PyTorch model development to distributed production. Primary audience: ML engineers in hedge funds.\n\n## ARCHITECTURAL FRAMEWORK\n### Core Principles\n1. Lifecycle first - organize around real ML system lifecycle, not tools alone\n2. Bounded domains - assign each concern clear boundaries\n3. Cross-cutting contracts - define lineage/security/traceability once, apply everywhere\n4. Topology separation - keep local dev, distributed training, batch, online inference distinct\n5. Python-first implementation - prefer Python unless platform forces otherwise\n6. Production realism - runnable patterns, not toy snippets\n7. Security by default - design input, not hardening pass\n8. Lineage by construction - every major artifact attributable and reconstructable\n9. Assistant augmentation - explicit auditable interfaces over canonical systems\n\n### Lifecycle Spine (canonical end-to-end)\n1. Data intake and dataset versioning\n2. Feature/transformation definition\n3. Experiment specification\n4. Training execution\n5. Evaluation and validation\n6. Model packaging\n7. Model registration and promotion\n8. Local serving\n9. Distributed training\n10. Batch inference\n11. Online inference\n12. Monitoring and alerting\n13. Cost governance\n14. Incident response and rollback\n\n## BOUNDED DOMAINS (8 system areas)\n1. Data - data intake, dataset versioning, schemas, provenance, data quality\n2. Training - PyTorch code, training config, GPU execution, distributed behavior, evaluation\n3. Artifact - model packaging, registry, versioning, promotion, compatibility constraints\n4. Serving - local inference, online/batch contracts, model loading, inference runtime\n5. Infrastructure - Terranix/OpenTofu, AWS resources, Lambda.ai, networking, storage\n6. Observability - metrics, logs, traces, drift monitoring, alerting\n7. Governance - security, IAM, secret handling, auditability, approval boundaries\n8. Cost - spend attribution, tagging, reporting, budgets, unit economics\n\n## CROSS-CUTTING CONTRACTS (7 system-wide invariants)\nA. Security baseline - identity, secrets, network, access, audit trails\nB. Data lineage baseline - source origin, version, schema, code reference, consumers\nC. Experiment traceability - code revision, environment, dataset/transformation versions, hyperparameters, artifacts\nD. Model artifact baseline - training origin, framework/serialization, schema, evaluation, serving modes\nE. Deployment baseline - model version, target environment, infra revision, rollback target, monitoring\nF. Prediction logging baseline - model version used, request ID, input schema, output capture, latency, traceability\nG. Cost attribution baseline - environment, workload type, owning system, experiment/job/deployment linkage\n\n## REFERENCE TOPOLOGIES (4 concrete deployment shapes)\nA. Local Development - Docker iteration, local serving, single-node GPU training\nB. Distributed Training - Lambda.ai multi-GPU/multi-node with Slurm coordination\nC. Batch Inference - AWS scheduled/event-driven with lineage and cost controls\nD. Online Inference - Kubernetes request/response with deployment/observability controls\n\n## CURRENT IMPLEMENTATION STATUS\n### ‚úÖ COMPLETED INFRASTRUCTURE\n- **Architecture Framework**: Ratified reference architecture skeleton, documentation TOC, contracts, domains, topologies\n- **Implementation Scaffolding**: Local vertical slice with Web UI contracts and runtime adapters\n- **Tooling Stack**: Nix dev shell, Docker-based local emulation (Floci, K3s, Slurm), Terranix/OpenTofu infrastructure\n- **Documentation Structure**: Quarto-based nbdev 3 with comprehensive wiki as living memory layer\n- **Governance Framework**: Spec-first implementation gating with promotion pipeline controls\n\n### ‚úÖ FIRST VERTICAL SLICE (EX-01, EX-02, EX-03)\n- Implemented in ml_deploy/vertical_slice.py via nbdev export from nbs/06_vertical_slice.qmd\n- Local training + MLflow traceability + artifact packaging + local inference + prediction logging\n- Success criteria: Full prediction traceability, artifact metadata sufficiency, local inference from packaged artifacts, request-level diagnosis, repeatable workflow\n\n### ‚úÖ WEB UI CONTRACTS\n- ml_deploy/webui_contracts.py from nbs/05_webui_contracts.qmd\n- Immutable notebook execution requests, normalized job specs, MLflow-linked run summaries\n\n### ‚úÖ EXECUTION BACKENDS\n- ml_deploy/execution_backends.py from nbs/08_execution_backends.qmd\n- Local execution adapter, Slurm/Kubernetes payload mapping, orchestration router\n\n### ‚úÖ GOVERNANCE GATES\n- ml_deploy/governance_gates.py with implementation transition logic\n- Blocks transition without explicit confirmation or passed spec quality gate\n- Aligns with distilled Allium spec requirements\n\n## TECHNOLOGY STACK\n### Core Technologies\n- Language: Python only (where practical)\n- OS: Linux only\n- ML Framework: PyTorch with GPU support\n- Experiment Tracking: MLflow with PostgreSQL backend + S3 artifact store\n- Documentation: nbdev 3 with Quarto rendering\n- Reproducible Development: Docker required, Nix as helper\n- Infrastructure: Terranix/OpenTofu JSON generation from flake+devenv\n\n### Compute Platforms\n- Local Development: Docker-based with Floci AWS emulation\n- Distributed Training: Lambda.ai with Slurm coordination/redundancy\n- Platform Services: AWS Kubernetes for non-Lambda.ai services\n\n### Default Stacks\n- Monitoring: Evidently + Prometheus + Grafana + MLflow\n- Cost Monitoring: AWS Cost Explorer/CUR/Athena + Python attribution layer\n- Assistant Integration: MLflow + observability + cost + infrastructure interrogation via MCP\n\n## WORKING MODE & CONSTRAINTS\n### Current Working Mode\n- **Specification-first**: Architecture and documentation quality priority\n- **Implementation gated**: Behind spec-quality readiness or explicit user authorization\n- **Wiki mandatory**: Synchronized with each substantive change\n\n### Hard Constraints\n1. Python only (where practical), Linux only, PyTorch only with GPU support\n2. Docker required for reproducible development (Nix as helper only)\n3. MLflow mandatory with PostgreSQL backend + S3 artifact store\n4. Local architecture replicates production storage/control planes\n5. Lambda.ai for distributed compute with Slurm orchestration\n6. AWS for platform services with Kubernetes substrate\n7. Notebook Web UI required for ML engineers to trigger runs without code edits\n8. Infrastructure: Nix-driven Terranix ‚Üí OpenTofu JSON generation\n9. Security, data lineage, experiment/model traceability, reproducibility permanent requirements\n\n## DOCUMENTATION STRUCTURE\n### Quarto-based Documentation\n- Source: notebooks in nbs/ (nbdev 3)\n- Generated: Python packages via nbdev-export, HTML docs via quarto render\n- Wiki: docs/wiki/ as living memory layer separate from documentation\n\n### Documentation Restructuring (COMPLETED)\n- ‚úÖ Phase 1: Analysis and Planning\n- ‚úÖ Phase 2: Content Restructuring (tutorials/, reference/ directories created)\n- ‚úÖ Phase 3: Configuration and Navigation (_quarto.yml updated)\n- ‚úÖ Phase 4: Testing and Quality Assurance\n\n### Navigation Structure\n- Tutorials: terminology glossary, getting started, concepts, workflow, advanced scenarios, migration guide\n- Reference: implementation patterns, API documentation\n- Full Documentation: 20+ technical sections covering all architecture domains\n\n## OPERATIONAL COMMANDS\n### Development Shell\n- nix develop - flake-defined toolchain with automatic .venv setup\n- uv sync - dependency management on drift or explicit request\n- nix develop -c start-jupyter - JupyterLab with ml_ops kernel\n\n### Docker Development\n- docker compose -f docker-compose.aws-emulator.yml -f docker-compose.dev.yml up -d\n- docker compose -f docker-compose.dev.yml down\n\n### Documentation\n- nix develop -c quarto render . --to html --no-execute\n- ./scripts/regenerate-html.sh - helper script for docs generation\n- ./scripts/finalize-task.sh - end-of-task workflow (export/render/tests)\n\n### Testing\n- uv run python -m unittest discover -s tests -q\n- Docker artifact regeneration: python scripts/generate-docker-artifacts.py\n\n## NEXT STEPS & PRIORITIES\n### Phase 2: Contract Automation & Runtime Integration\n- Connect governance gates into orchestration paths\n- Implement automated validation for Web UI contracts\n- Add real-time compliance checks for MLflow operations\n\n### Phase 3: Multi-Topology Implementation\n- Local vertical slice ‚Üí distributed training ‚Üí batch inference ‚Üí online serving\n- Lambda.ai Slurm integration for distributed workloads\n- AWS batch inference with lineage controls\n- Online inference with rollout/rollback capabilities\n\n### Phase 4: Web UI Execution Flow\n- Immutable notebook semantics with source validation\n- Version-controlled execution requests\n- Connect runtime adapters to actual schedulers\n\n### Phase 5: Observability & Monitoring\n- Enhanced metrics collection with cost attribution\n- Drift detection for model performance\n- Alerting system with thresholds and notifications\n\n## KEY DECISIONS NEEDED\n1. Scope prioritization: distributed training vs batch inference next\n2. Resource allocation: cloud infrastructure vs local development focus\n3. Team structure: ML engineering vs DevOps responsibilities\n\n## TECHNICAL DEBT AREAS\n1. Missing scheduler client integrations (Slurm/Kubernetes)\n2. Incomplete observability features beyond MLflow+Floci\n3. Need for automated artifact freshness validation in CI/CD\n\n## BEST PRACTICES ESTABLISHED\n1. Documentation self-sufficiency requirements\n2. Spec-first development patterns with governance gating\n3. Contract-first implementation approach\n4. Wiki as living memory layer for continuous knowledge capture\n\n## WIKI MANAGEMENT PROCESS\n- At task start: Read index.md, relevant routed pages, raw files as needed\n- During task: Discover durable facts, decisions, constraints, open questions ‚Üí fold into wiki\n- Before final response: Update all relevant wiki pages if substantive changes occurred\n- Page conventions: Compact, high-signal, include purpose, reading context, links, facts\n- Quality bar: Help future agents answer what exists, how to run it, constraints, recent changes, important files","createdAt":"2026-05-15T18:55:32.611Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp7a28sn_3a585eb07139","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"WIKI COMPREHENSIVE MEMORY CAPTURE - Complete Project Knowledge Base\n\n## PROJECT ","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T18:55:32.611Z","version":1},"mem_mp7ab09e_a52cd07b6ee3":{"concepts":[],"content":"SOFTWARE STACK STRUCTURAL GAPS - Comprehensive Gap Analysis\n\n## CRITICAL STRUCTURAL GAPS (High Priority)\n\n### 1. Production-Grade Serving Infrastructure\n**Current Coverage**: 30%\n**Critical Gap**: No actual serving service implementation\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- Model serving framework (FastAPI, TorchServe, or similar)\n- Production-grade batch processing orchestration  \n- Online inference service with request/response handling\n- Canary/rollback deployment logic\n- Production monitoring integration\n- Load balancing and auto-scaling\n- Health check endpoints\n- Request/response logging and tracing\n- Model hot-reloading capabilities\n- Service mesh integration\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n- ‚úÖ Local inference from packaged artifacts (first vertical slice)\n- ‚úÖ Web UI contracts for immutable notebook execution\n- ‚úÖ Execution backend adapters (local, Slurm, Kubernetes)\n- ‚ĚĆ No actual serving service or API endpoint\n\n### 2. Distributed Training Implementation  \n**Current Coverage**: 25%\n**Critical Gap**: Lambda.ai/Slurm integration only exists as payload mapping\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- Slurm client library integration (e.g., pyslurm, subprocess integration)\n- Lambda.ai SDK integration for job submission/monitoring\n- Distributed training coordination logic\n- Multi-GPU training support (torch.distributed, DeepSpeed)\n- Redundancy/failure handling patterns\n- Checkpoint coordination across nodes\n- Network topology optimization\n- Resource allocation and scheduling\n- Job status polling and lifecycle management\n- Fault tolerance and recovery mechanisms\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n- ‚úÖ Slurm job spec mapping (`map_to_slurm_job_spec`)\n- ‚úÖ Kubernetes job spec mapping (`map_to_kubernetes_job_spec`)\n- ‚ĚĆ No actual Slurm client implementation\n- ‚ĚĆ No Lambda.ai integration\n- ‚ĚĆ No distributed training execution\n\n### 3. Security & Identity Implementation\n**Current Coverage**: 15%  \n**Critical Gap**: No actual security implementation\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- Identity provider integration (Okta, Auth0, AWS Cognito, Keycloak)\n- Policy enforcement engine (Open Policy Agent, custom RBAC)\n- Secret management (AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault, environment variables)\n- Audit logging system (structured logs, log aggregation)\n- Network security controls (firewall rules, VPC setup, security groups)\n- TLS/SSL certificate management\n- Token validation and refresh logic\n- Access control middleware\n- Security scanning and vulnerability assessment\n- Compliance reporting\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n- ‚úÖ Security baseline contracts\n- ‚úÖ OIDC-backed authorization architecture  \n- ‚úÖ Capability catalogs concept\n- ‚ĚĆ No actual authentication system\n- ‚ĚĆ No IAM/policy implementation\n- ‚ĚĆ No secret management\n- ‚ĚĆ No audit logging\n\n## HIGH PRIORITY GAPS\n\n### 4. Data Pipeline Implementation\n**Current Coverage**: 20%\n**High Priority Gap**: No actual data pipeline\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- Data ingestion pipelines (Apache NiFi, custom Python scripts, Airflow)\n- Dataset versioning system (DVC, Git LFS, custom metadata store)\n- Feature store (Feast, Tecton, custom Redis/PostgreSQL solution)\n- Data validation framework (Great Expectations, custom validation)\n- Data quality monitoring and alerts\n- Data lineage tracking implementation (Apache Atlas, custom graph)\n- Data transformation orchestration\n- Data catalog and discovery interface\n- Data retention and archival policies\n- Data governance and compliance tools\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n- ‚úÖ Data lineage contracts defined\n- ‚úÖ Dataset versioning concepts\n- ‚úÖ Transformation baseline contracts\n- ‚ĚĆ No actual data ingestion pipeline\n- ‚ĚĆ No data versioning system\n- ‚ĚĆ No feature store implementation\n\n### 5. Production-Grade Observability\n**Current Coverage**: 30%\n**High Priority Gap**: No actual implementation\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- Prometheus metrics collection and scraping\n- Grafana dashboards and visualization\n- Evidently model/data quality monitoring integration\n- Drift detection algorithms and models\n- Alerting system (Alertmanager, custom notifications)\n- Cost tracking and attribution implementation\n- Log aggregation and analysis (Loki, ELK stack)\n- Distributed tracing (Jaeger, Zipkin)\n- Service health monitoring\n- Performance monitoring and SLA tracking\n- Business metrics tracking\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n- ‚úÖ Monitoring stack definition (Evidently + Prometheus + Grafana + MLflow)\n- ‚úÖ Cost attribution baseline contracts\n- ‚úÖ Prediction logging baseline\n- ‚ĚĆ No actual Prometheus/Grafana setup\n- ‚ĚĆ No Evidently integration\n- ‚ĚĆ No drift detection system\n\n## MEDIUM PRIORITY GAPS\n\n### 6. Infrastructure as Code Execution\n**Current Coverage**: 40%\n**Medium Priority Gap**: No actual infrastructure deployment\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- OpenTofu CLI integration and automation\n- Cloud provider authentication and credential management\n- Infrastructure state backend (S3, DynamoDB, PostgreSQL)\n- Deployment orchestration and pipeline automation\n- Infrastructure-as-code testing and validation\n- Environment-specific configuration management\n- Infrastructure monitoring and alerting\n- Cost optimization and resource utilization tracking\n- Security scanning for infrastructure\n- Disaster recovery and backup automation\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n- ‚úÖ Terranix module structure defined\n- ‚úÖ OpenTofu JSON generation approach documented\n- ‚úÖ Docker artifacts generated from Nix definitions\n- ‚ĚĆ No actual OpenTofu deployment pipeline\n- ‚ĚĆ No cloud infrastructure provisioning\n\n### 7. Model Registry & Promotion\n**Current Coverage**: 35%\n**Medium Priority Gap**: No actual registry system\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- Model registry backend (MLflow Registry, custom API, cloud registry)\n- Model version management and metadata tracking\n- Promotion workflow automation (CI/CD integration)\n- Model lifecycle policies and automation\n- Model compatibility checking and validation\n- Model artifact storage and retrieval\n- Model approval workflows\n- Model deployment coordination\n- Model performance tracking and comparison\n- Model retirement and archival policies\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n- ‚úÖ Model artifact baseline contracts\n- ‚úÖ Model version records in first vertical slice\n- ‚úÖ Promotion pipeline gate logic\n- ‚ĚĆ No actual model registry\n- ‚ĚĆ No model version management\n- ‚ĚĆ No promotion workflow automation\n\n### 8. Web UI Implementation\n**Current Coverage**: 20%\n**Medium Priority Gap**: No actual user interface\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- Frontend framework (React, Vue, Angular, Streamlit)\n- User authentication interface (login, registration, session management)\n- Notebook upload/selection interface (file upload, git integration)\n- Execution monitoring dashboard (real-time status, logs, metrics)\n- Results visualization and analysis interface\n- Model management interface (view, compare, deploy models)\n- Cost tracking and budgeting interface\n- Administration panel (users, permissions, system settings)\n- API documentation and testing interface\n- User preference and profile management\n\nCURRENT STATE:\n- ‚úÖ Web UI backend contracts\n- ‚úÖ Immutable notebook execution semantics\n- ‚úÖ Execution orchestration routing\n- ‚ĚĆ No actual Web UI frontend\n- ‚ĚĆ No user authentication interface\n\n## INTEGRATION GAPS\n\n### 9. End-to-End Integration\n**Current Coverage**: 15%\n**Medium Priority Gap**: No complete end-to-end flow\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- Complete local-to-production pipeline orchestration\n- Cross-component data flow coordination\n- Error handling and recovery across components\n- Transaction guarantees across distributed systems\n- Data consistency across services\n- Service communication and API integration\n- Configuration management across environments\n- Deployment pipeline integration\n- Monitoring and logging correlation across services\n- Performance optimization across the stack\n\n### 10. Operational Tooling\n**Current Coverage**: 25%\n**Low Priority Gap**: Development tooling exists but no operational tooling\n\nMISSING COMPONENTS:\n- Production deployment scripts and automation\n- Platform monitoring and alerting for the stack itself\n- Backup and disaster recovery automation\n- Performance optimization tools for the platform\n- Cost optimization and resource management tools\n- Security scanning and vulnerability management\n- Compliance and audit automation\n- Incident response and management tools\n- Change management and deployment coordination\n- Capacity planning and scaling automation\n\n## GAP ANALYSIS SUMMARY TABLE\n\n| **Area** | **Current Coverage** | **Critical Gap** | **Impact** | **Priority** |\n|----------|-------------------|------------------|------------|--------------|\n| **Serving Infrastructure** | 30% | Production-grade serving | High | Critical |\n| **Distributed Training** | 25% | Actual Lambda.ai/Slurm execution | High | Critical |\n| **Security Implementation** | 15% | Actual auth/policy enforcement | Critical | Critical |\n| **Data Pipeline** | 20% | Actual data ingestion/management | High | High |\n| **Observability** | 30% | Production monitoring stack | Medium | High |\n| **Infrastructure as Code** | 40% | Actual cloud deployment | Medium | Medium |\n| **Model Registry** | 35% | Actual model management | Medium | Medium |\n| **Web UI** | 20% | Actual user interface | Medium | Medium |\n| **End-to-End Integration** | 15% | Complete pipeline flow | Medium | Medium |\n| **Operational Tooling** | 25% | Production operations tools | Low | Low |\n\n## NEXT STEPS FOR GAP CLOSING\n\n### Phase 1: Critical Security and Serving (Blockers)\n1. Implement authentication and authorization system\n2. Build production-grade model serving framework\n3. Establish secret management and audit logging\n\n### Phase 2: Core Infrastructure and Data (Foundation)\n4. Implement data ingestion and versioning pipeline\n5. Build distributed training execution capability\n6. Set up production observability stack\n\n### Phase 3: Advanced Capabilities (Differentiation)\n7. Implement complete model registry and promotion\n8. Build end-to-end integration pipeline\n9. Develop operational tooling and automation\n\n### Phase 4: User Experience (Accessibility)\n10. Build complete Web UI frontend\n11. Implement administration and monitoring interfaces\n12. Add user preference and configuration management\n\n## RISK MITIGATION\n\n### High Risk Mitigation:\n- Security gaps: Implement authentication first before other services\n- Serving gaps: Use existing local inference as foundation for production serving\n- Training gaps: Start with single-node training before distributed\n\n### Medium Risk Mitigation:\n- Data gaps: Implement basic data validation before complex pipelines\n- Observability gaps: Start with basic logging before full monitoring stack\n- Integration gaps: Build incrementally with clear interfaces\n\n### Low Risk Mitigation:\n- Operational gaps: Can be implemented concurrently with other features\n- UI gaps: Can be added incrementally as features are built\n\nThis gap analysis provides a roadmap for systematic closure of structural gaps while maintaining the architectural foundation and specification-first approach.","createdAt":"2026-05-15T19:02:21.453Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp7ab09e_a52cd07b6ee3","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"SOFTWARE STACK STRUCTURAL GAPS - Comprehensive Gap Analysis\n\n## CRITICAL STRUCTU","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T19:02:21.453Z","version":1},"mem_mp7cwou6_5df3ed9b119b":{"concepts":[],"content":"TRADITIONAL AUTH / ROLES / POLICY REFERENCE POSTURE\n\nCANONICAL POSTURE:\n- OIDC-backed authentication for humans\n- scoped service identities / cloud federation for automation\n- centralized authorization engine for policy decisions\n- RBAC for human users plus capability catalogs for subsystems\n- policy-as-code evaluation for privileged actions\n- audit trails for every allow/deny decision\n\nNEW REFERENCE DOC:\n- nbs/reference/03_Security_Authorization_and_Policy.qmd\n- Describes the stack's traditional enterprise auth model in narrative form\n- Covers identity classes, core roles, service principals, capability families, policy dimensions, enforcement points, deny conditions, and request lifecycle\n\nROLE MODEL:\n- SystemAdmin, SecurityAdmin, PlatformAdmin, DataAdmin, ProjectAdmin, Developer, Analyst, Viewer, Auditor\n- service principals for Web UI, MLflow proxy, execution adapters, docs serving, CI, and MCP tooling\n\nCAPABILITY FAMILIES:\n- data, training/experiments, artifacts/registry, serving, infrastructure, observability, governance/policy, cost/chargeback, notebook execution\n\nPOLICY DIMENSIONS:\n- identity, resource, action, environment, sensitivity, approval state, provenance\n\nENFORCEMENT POINTS:\n- notebook Web UI/backend\n- MLflow reverse proxy\n- execution orchestrator and backend adapters\n- infra apply path\n- assistant/MCP tooling\n\nGAP ANALYSIS IMPACT:\n- Security gap now explicitly references the documented OIDC + RBAC + centralized policy posture as the implementation blueprint\n\nWIKI UPDATES:\n- decisions/security-authorization-architecture.md links to the new reference page\n- current-state.md notes the new doc and still marks implementation as missing\n- gaps/software-stack-gaps.md now treats the documented posture as the blueprint for implementation","createdAt":"2026-05-15T20:15:12.314Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp7cwou6_5df3ed9b119b","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"TRADITIONAL AUTH / ROLES / POLICY REFERENCE POSTURE\n\nCANONICAL POSTURE:\n- OIDC-b","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T20:15:12.314Z","version":1},"mem_mp7dg404_bb4f833f9e89":{"concepts":[],"content":"FasAPI-removal / framework-neutral serving posture\n\nFACT: The reference stack is now intentionally framework-neutral on the serving layer. FastAPI is not part of the reference stack and should not be mentioned in active docs or implementation guidance.\n\nDOCS UPDATED:\n- nbs/02_02-model_development.qmd\n- nbs/reference/01_Implementation_Patterns.qmd\n- nbs/tutorials/05_Advanced_Scenarios.qmd\n- nbs/tutorials/06_Migration_Guide.qmd\n- docs/wiki/contracts/security-baseline.md\n- docs/wiki/decisions/nbdev-framework-decision.md\n- docs/wiki/gaps/software-stack-gaps.md\n- docs/wiki/current-state.md\n- docs/wiki/index.md\n- docs/wiki/revisions/2026-05-16-framework-neutral-serving-no-fastapi.md\n- docs/wiki/log.md\n\nHISTORICAL REVISION RECORDS: Some archival revisions were also generalized to remove FastAPI references while preserving the underlying historical intent.","createdAt":"2026-05-15T20:30:18.433Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp7dg404_bb4f833f9e89","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"FasAPI-removal / framework-neutral serving posture\n\nFACT: The reference stack is","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T20:30:18.433Z","version":1},"mem_mp7du8dl_8d07db22d8a5":{"concepts":[],"content":"DOCS COMPACTION / LINE-LIMIT POLICY\n\nFACT: The active source docs (nbs/*.qmd and docs/wiki/*.md that the repo owns) were compacted to stay under 500 lines per file.\n\nCHANGES:\n- Rewrote reference pages:\n  - nbs/reference/01_Implementation_Patterns.qmd\n  - nbs/reference/02_API_Documentation.qmd\n  - nbs/reference/03_Security_Authorization_and_Policy.qmd\n- Rewrote tutorial pages:\n  - nbs/tutorials/03_Concepts_and_Architecture.qmd\n  - nbs/tutorials/04_End_to_End_Workflow.qmd\n  - nbs/tutorials/05_Advanced_Scenarios.qmd\n  - nbs/tutorials/06_Migration_Guide.qmd\n- Shortened decision pages:\n  - docs/wiki/decisions/mlflow-storage-sync-strategy.md\n  - docs/wiki/decisions/nix-containerization-boundary.md\n  - docs/wiki/decisions/nix-terranix-opentofu-boundary.md\n  - docs/wiki/decisions/mlflow-notebook-execution-contract.md\n- Updated wiki log/current-state and source summaries to reflect the compacted docs.\n\nOBSERVATION:\n- Quarto-generated _docs sidecars can still exceed 500 lines even when the source qmd is compact; those would need a second pass or a keep-md policy change if the goal is to eliminate every over-limit tracked markdown artifact.\n","createdAt":"2026-05-15T20:41:17.286Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp7du8dl_8d07db22d8a5","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"DOCS COMPACTION / LINE-LIMIT POLICY\n\nFACT: The active source docs (nbs/*.qmd and","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T20:41:17.286Z","version":1},"mem_mp7elt2b_6764513759ff":{"concepts":[],"content":"AWS / FLOCI-ALIGNED IMPLEMENTATION PATH\n\nFACT: For the biggest remaining gaps, prefer AWS-native services that Floci can emulate locally to preserve parity between local and cloud.\n\nRECOMMENDED ALIGNMENTS:\n- Security / identity / secrets / audit: OIDC at the edge + IAM + STS + Secrets Manager + CloudWatch\n- Artifact / registry storage: S3 + PostgreSQL + MLflow Registry\n- Observability: CloudWatch + MLflow\n- Infrastructure: Terranix/OpenTofu generated AWS resources with Floci local emulation\n\nCONSEQUENCES ON OTHER SUBSYSTEMS:\n- Web UI/backend must preserve principal identity and role/capability context end-to-end\n- Execution backends must expect environment-scoped credentials and object-store URLs\n- Model registry and artifact URLs must stay stable across local/cloud profiles\n- Logging/metrics names should stay aligned between local emulation and cloud\n- Promotion and mutation paths must remain approval-aware and auditable\n- Non-Floci-native areas such as Lambda.ai/Slurm remain topology-specific and should not be forced into AWS parity\n\nWIKI / DOCS UPDATED:\n- docs/wiki/decisions/aws-floci-aligned-implementation-path.md\n- nbs/tutorials/05_Advanced_Scenarios.qmd\n- nbs/reference/03_Security_Authorization_and_Policy.qmd\n- docs/wiki/gaps/software-stack-gaps.md\n- docs/wiki/decisions/security-authorization-architecture.md\n- docs/wiki/current-state.md\n- docs/wiki/index.md\n- docs/wiki/decisions/index.md","createdAt":"2026-05-15T21:02:43.808Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp7elt2b_6764513759ff","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"AWS / FLOCI-ALIGNED IMPLEMENTATION PATH\n\nFACT: For the biggest remaining gaps, p","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-15T21:02:43.808Z","version":1},"mem_mp9lgyex_97887c3e914e":{"concepts":[],"content":"Completed QMD to RST conversion for ML Deploy documentation:\n- Moved missing files from _proc/ to nbs/: 00_core.qmd, 00_introduction.qmd, 05_webui_contracts.qmd, 09_notebook_intake.qmd, 12_system_interaction_analysis.qmd, 13_opentofu_infra.qmd\n- Created missing files based on wiki summaries: 14_infrastructure_mcp.qmd, 15_aws_emulator.qmd, 16_terranix_infra.qmd\n- Converted all 53 QMD files to RST format in docs/sphinx/source/\n- Updated docs/wiki/current-state.md to reflect documentation-complete state\n- Verified successful Sphinx documentation build with 0 warnings","createdAt":"2026-05-17T09:50:27.121Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mp9lgyex_97887c3e914e","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"Completed QMD to RST conversion for ML Deploy documentation:\n- Moved missing fil","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-17T09:50:27.121Z","version":1},"mem_mpb36nq2_8c958cc22cc0":{"concepts":[],"content":"Completed modular devenv setup with Terranix integration. Fixed critical devenv.nix configuration issue (startJupyter string ‚Üí derivation), validated modular devenv_modules structure loads correctly, created comprehensive wiki documentation for modular setup, separated local/cloud profiles with appropriate module configurations, resolved package list type errors in devenv configuration, and fixed environment variable handling in start-jupyter script. Terranix integration and final environment variable handling remain pending.","createdAt":"2026-05-18T10:54:05.972Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mpb36nq2_8c958cc22cc0","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"Completed modular devenv setup with Terranix integration. Fixed critical devenv.","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-18T10:54:05.972Z","version":1},"mem_mpb6k6wt_695b3299d484":{"concepts":[],"content":"Created empty.nix module in devenv_modules/modules/ for testing modular devenv loading. The module is empty and ready to be extended. Wiki documentation updated with empty module details.","createdAt":"2026-05-18T12:28:36.219Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mpb6k6wt_695b3299d484","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"Created empty.nix module in devenv_modules/modules/ for testing modular devenv l","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-18T12:28:36.219Z","version":1},"mem_mpb70v7t_a69ca89463e2":{"concepts":[],"content":"Created local Opentofu setup module in devenv_modules/modules/local.nix. The module includes local OpenTofu configuration with Docker-based infrastructure: Traefik reverse proxy, PostgreSQL for MLflow, MLflow server, Floci (LocalStack) for AWS emulation, and Floci bootstrap for bucket initialization. Updated devenv.nix to import local.nix in localDev profile.","createdAt":"2026-05-18T12:41:34.187Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mpb70v7t_a69ca89463e2","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"Created local Opentofu setup module in devenv_modules/modules/local.nix. The mod","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-18T12:41:34.187Z","version":1},"mem_mpb7xpce_42f4aba16459":{"concepts":[],"content":"Updated local.nix to use Minikube instead of K3s for local Kubernetes. Minikube is simpler for local development with endpoint at localhost:8443.","createdAt":"2026-05-18T13:07:06.249Z","files":[],"id":"mem_mpb7xpce_42f4aba16459","isLatest":true,"sessionIds":[],"sourceObservationIds":[],"strength":7,"supersedes":[],"title":"Updated local.nix to use Minikube instead of K3s for local Kubernetes. Minikube ","type":"fact","updatedAt":"2026-05-18T13:07:06.249Z","version":1}}␀␀␀ĪĀ␀ĆŖĢˇ